  <div class="thesis-section">
    <div class="thesis-label">Central Thesis</div>
    <div class="thesis-text">
      <h2>How does Islamophobia function when it is organized by the state rather than by electoral campaigns or public hate groups?</h2>
      <p>China's treatment of Uyghur Muslims in Xinjiang reveals a form of Islamophobia that extends beyond private prejudice or individual hate speech. In this project, we argue that Islamophobia in China operates through state power — Uyghur Muslim identity is repeatedly framed as extremism, then governed through counterterrorism law, religious regulation, surveillance technology, detention, forced labor, and propaganda. The central claim is that Islamophobia in China works by transforming Uyghur Muslim identity into a security category, targeting religion, ethnicity, language, culture, and economic survival simultaneously.</p>
    </div>
