<!-- COUNTRY PROFILE -->
<div id="page-profile" class="page">
  <div class="page-hero">
    <div class="page-number">Section 01</div>
    <h1>Country Profile: China, Xinjiang, &amp; Uyghur Muslims</h1>
    <p>A demographic and geographic grounding of the Xinjiang Uyghur Autonomous Region</p>
  </div>
  <div class="content-area">
    <p>Xinjiang is officially known as the Xinjiang Uyghur Autonomous Region and is located in northwest China. Surrounded by many different countries, Xinjiang has built a lasting reputation in Central Asia because of trade routes, cultural exchanges, and migrations. This also makes the region strategically important to the Chinese government, which views Xinjiang as both a homeland for many ethnic groups and an essential zone for national security, border control, and economic development.</p>

    <h2>Uyghur Identity</h2>
    <p>Uyghurs are a predominantly Sunni Muslim people who speak Turkic. Their historic homeland is Xinjiang — which many Uyghurs describe as East Turkestan. Uyghur identity is shaped by religion, language, family networks, and cultural traditions that are quite distinct from the Han Chinese who also inhabit the region.</p>

    <div class="pull-quote">
      <p>Xinjiang remains a multiethnic and religiously diverse region, where Uyghurs maintain strong communities and cultural ties.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>Demographics</h2>
    <p>According to China's 2020 census, Xinjiang's total population was <strong>25,852,345</strong>. The Uyghur population was <strong>11,624,257</strong> — comprising 44.96% of the region — while Han Chinese residents made up 42.24%. These numbers confirm Xinjiang's multiethnic character.</p>

    <div class="image-figure">
      <img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="Pew Research Center chart showing birth rates in Xinjiang have fallen sharply, particularly in Kashgar prefecture">
      <div class="image-caption">Source: Pew Research Center, analysis of National Bureau of Statistics of China data — "Measuring Religion in China." Birth rates in the majority-Uyghur Kashgar prefecture fell from 23.2 (2008) to 6.5 (2022).</div>
    </div>

    <h2>Why This Context Matters</h2>
    <p>Islamophobia in Xinjiang cannot be separated from ethnic policies around religion, language, and culture, migration, economic development, and state security. Uyghur Muslims are targeted because their religious and cultural identity is often treated by the Chinese state as a sign of separatism, foreign influence, or extremism. Anti-Muslim suspicion overlaps with suspicion toward Uyghur ethnicity, Central Asian cultural ties, and claims to regional identity.</p>

    <div class="info-box">
      <h4>Key Geographic Context</h4>
      <p>Xinjiang's status as a strategic borderland — sharing borders with Russia, Mongolia, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Tajikistan, Afghanistan, Pakistan, and India — helps explain why the Chinese government has built an intensive system of surveillance, policing, religious regulation, and forced assimilation there. The region is also rich in natural resources, including oil and gas, that are economically critical to the state.</p>
    </div>

