    <div class="page-number">Section 02</div>
    <h1>Historical Background: From Borderland Control to the "War on Terror"</h1>
    <p>How decades of state policy transformed Uyghur Muslim identity into a security threat</p>
  </div>
  <div class="content-area">
    <p>The current repression of Uyghur Muslims did not appear suddenly. It developed through a history of borderland control, clashes over assimilation, and post-2014 counterterrorism policies that treated Uyghur Muslim identity as a threat to the state. Xinjiang has been politically important to the Chinese state because of its size, natural resources, geography, and cultural difference from China's Han majority regions.</p>

    <h2>Deepening Tensions</h2>
    <p>As the state became stricter in migration, surveillance, economic development, and assimilation, the tension deepened between Uyghur Muslims and the state. Many Uyghurs experienced these policies as threats to their culture, employment opportunities, and political autonomy. After the 2009 violence in Urumqi, the regional capital, the Chinese government increasingly explained problems or resistance in Xinjiang as terrorism, separatism, or religious extremism.</p>

    <div class="pull-quote">
      <p>This labeling mattered because it shifted the issue away from questions about ethnic inequality, religious freedom, or state repression — and toward a security narrative in which Uyghur Muslim identity itself could be treated as dangerous.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>Farish Noor and the "War on Terror" Framework</h2>
    <p>Farish Noor's reading on the "War on Terror" helps explain this shift. Noor argues that after 9/11, governments around the world adopted the language of terrorism and extremism to expand state power and marginalize Muslim communities. China's policies in Xinjiang follow this broader pattern: counterterrorism language allows ordinary religious and cultural practices to be redefined as signs of extremism.</p>

    <h2>The 2014 Turning Point</h2>
    <div class="law-box">
      <h4>Strike Hard Campaign against Violent Terrorism (2014)</h4>
      <p>Under this campaign, China intensified policing, surveillance, detention, religious restrictions, and reeducation in Xinjiang. The campaign also expanded the definition of "suspicious behavior" — ordinary expressions of Uyghur Muslim identity, such as religious study, mosque attendance, certain clothing, fasting, long beards, or maintaining connections abroad, could be interpreted as signs of extremism.</p>
    </div>

    <p>This history shows that Islamophobia in Xinjiang developed through a security framework built by the government. The Chinese state created justification for a broad system of control over Muslim religious and cultural life by linking Uyghur identity to terrorism and separatism.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- LEGAL -->
<div id="page-legal" class="page">
  <div class="page-hero">
    <div class="page-number">Section 03</div>
    <h1>Legal Restrictions on Muslim Citizens</h1>
    <p>How Chinese law criminalizes everyday Uyghur Muslim life</p>
  </div>
  <div class="content-area">
    <p>China's legal system does not only punish violence. In Xinjiang, it also treats everyday signs of Uyghur Muslim life — halal food, clothing, beards, names, religious education, and mosques — as suspicious. This is structural Islamophobia embedded in law.</p>

    <div class="law-box">
      <h4>Xinjiang's 2017 "Regulation on De-extremification"</h4>
      <p>This law labels many normal religious and cultural practices as possible signs of extremism. It targets: expanding halal rules beyond food, wearing face-covering clothing, growing certain beards, using religious names, having religious marriages outside state rules, and owning materials the state considers extremist.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>Structural Islamophobia in Law</h2>
    <p>This is a major example of structural Islamophobia because the law connects Islam with danger. Practices that are usually seen as religion, culture, or personal choice are treated as signs of radicalization. For Uyghur Muslims, this means the state can control both public and private life — including clothing, reading materials, children's names, marriage, halal practices, and visible expressions of faith.</p>

    <div class="pull-quote">
      <p>Muslim identity becomes something people have to prove is harmless. Uyghur Muslims are not only punished for breaking laws — they are also controlled for seeming too religious, too culturally different, or not assimilated enough.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>"Sinicization" of Religion (2024)</h2>
    <p>Recent religious rules show that this control has continued. In 2024, Xinjiang's revised religious regulations focused on the "Sinicization" of religion — meaning religious practice is expected to fit Chinese Communist Party ideas, socialist values, and "Chinese characteristics." For Uyghur Muslims, mosques, religious leaders, religious education, and public expressions of Islam are only allowed when they match the state's political goals.</p>

    <div class="info-box">
      <h4>Key Legal Principle</h4>
      <p>Islam is not completely banned in Xinjiang — but it is tightly controlled and treated as suspicious unless it obeys the state. This approach is more insidious than an outright ban because it forces compliance while providing a veneer of religious tolerance.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>Prohibited Practices Under State Law</h2>
    <div class="surveillance-grid">
      <div class="surv-cell"><div class="surv-icon">🕌</div><h4>Mosque Attendance</h4><p>Monitored; unauthorized worship treated as extremism</p></div>
      <div class="surv-cell"><div class="surv-icon">📿</div><h4>Religious Names</h4><p>Certain Islamic names banned or restricted for children</p></div>
      <div class="surv-cell"><div class="surv-icon">👗</div><h4>Clothing</h4><p>Face-covering clothing and "abnormal" beards prohibited</p></div>
      <div class="surv-cell"><div class="surv-icon">🍖</div><h4>Halal Expansion</h4><p>Applying halal rules beyond food labeled extremist</p></div>
      <div class="surv-cell"><div class="surv-icon">📖</div><h4>Religious Texts</h4><p>Unapproved materials classified as extremist content</p></div>
      <div class="surv-cell"><div class="surv-icon">💍</div><h4>Marriage</h4><p>Religious marriages outside state registration prohibited</p></div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- POLITICAL -->
<div id="page-political" class="page">
  <div class="page-hero">
    <div class="page-number">Section 04</div>
    <h1>Political Rhetoric: State Securitization Without Elections</h1>
    <p>How Islamophobic politics appears through official discourse rather than campaign speeches</p>
  </div>
  <div class="content-area">
    <p>Because China lacks competitive electoral campaigns, Islamophobic politics in this case appears less through campaign speeches and more through official state rhetoric that presents Uyghur Muslim identity as a counterterrorism problem.</p>

    <h2>The "Three Evils" Framework</h2>
    <p>Chinese officials often describe policies in Xinjiang as necessary to fight the "three evils" of terrorism, separatism, and religious extremism. This rhetoric is powerful because it makes harsh state policies appear defensive and reasonable to Chinese citizens. If Uyghur Muslim identity is framed as a possible source of terrorism, then surveillance, detention, religious restrictions, ideological education, and forced assimilation can be presented as public safety measures rather than revealing their discriminatory nature.</p>

    <div class="pull-quote">
      <p>The language of counterterrorism shifts attention away from Uyghur Muslim rights and toward the state's claim of protecting national security, ethnic unity, and social stability.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>How Rhetoric Becomes Policy</h2>
    <p>The state's rhetoric is central to how Islamophobia functions in China. It does not always say directly that Islam is the enemy. Rather, it suggests that certain forms of Islamic practice, Uyghur cultural identity, foreign religious influence, or refusal to assimilate may lead to extremism. Because the definition of extremism is so broad, ordinary Muslim practices can be grouped into suspicion categories, further supporting discriminatory policies.</p>

    <div class="info-box">
      <h4>Contrast with Electoral Islamophobia</h4>
      <p>In countries with competitive elections, politicians may use anti-Muslim language to win votes or appeal to nationalist fears. China works differently: the Chinese Communist Party controls the political system and does not rely on open electoral competition. As a result, Islamophobia operates through official speeches, government documents, state media, police campaigns, and legal language that repeatedly links Xinjiang, Uyghurs, and Islam to extremism.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>Key Rhetorical Moves</h2>
    <div class="law-box">
      <h4>Defensive Framing</h4>
      <p>"Vocational education and training centers" — the government's term for what international observers document as detention camps. The framing presents coercive confinement as benevolent education.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="law-box">
      <h4>Stability Imperative</h4>
      <p>The constant invocation of "stability" and "social harmony" provides cover for suppressing any expression of Uyghur cultural distinctiveness, framing cultural preservation as an existential threat.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="law-box">
      <h4>Counterterrorism Legitimacy</h4>
      <p>By aligning itself with global post-9/11 counterterrorism discourse, China borrowed international legitimacy for domestic repression — positioning critics as terrorism enablers.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- SURVEILLANCE -->
<div id="page-surveillance" class="page">
  <div class="page-hero">
    <div class="page-number">Section 05</div>
    <h1>Surveillance, Emergency Regulations, &amp; Terrorism Restrictions</h1>
    <p>How technology is leveraged to implement Islamophobic state policies at scale</p>
  </div>
  <div class="content-area">
    <p>The surveillance state in Xinjiang demonstrates how technology is leveraged to implement Islamophobic state policies. On a day-to-day basis, the lives of Uyghur Muslims in Xinjiang are monitored, categorized, and converted into data that can trigger interrogation, movement restrictions, or detention.</p>

    <h2>The IJOP System</h2>
    <p>Human Rights Watch has reported extensively on how Chinese authorities use a mass surveillance system called the <strong>Integrated Joint Operations Platform (IJOP)</strong> to collect and analyze personal information on Uyghurs. The system gathers data from police checkpoints, cameras, phone monitoring, identity checks, and other sources, then flags people considered suspicious using algorithms. A person does not need to commit a violent act to become a target — ordinary details of daily life can be treated as warning signs.</p>

    <div class="surveillance-grid">
      <div class="surv-cell"><div class="surv-icon">📹</div><h4>CCTV Network</h4><p>Pervasive camera coverage with facial recognition across Xinjiang</p></div>
      <div class="surv-cell"><div class="surv-icon">📱</div><h4>Phone Monitoring</h4><p>Mandatory app installations; VPN use flagged as extremism</p></div>
      <div class="surv-cell"><div class="surv-icon">🧬</div><h4>Biometric Data</h4><p>DNA samples, iris scans, voice prints, and fingerprints collected</p></div>
      <div class="surv-cell"><div class="surv-icon">🚧</div><h4>Checkpoints</h4><p>ID checks and facial scans at frequent intervals throughout cities</p></div>
      <div class="surv-cell"><div class="surv-icon">🏠</div><h4>Home Stays</h4><p>State officials assigned to live in Uyghur homes to monitor behavior</p></div>
      <div class="surv-cell"><div class="surv-icon">🤖</div><h4>Predictive Algorithms</h4><p>IJOP flags "pre-crime" risks based on religion and social networks</p></div>
    </div>

    <h2>Identity as Risk</h2>
    <p>This surveillance system is especially dangerous because it turns identity into risk. For Uyghur Muslims, religious and cultural life becomes part of a security profile. Visiting a mosque, having relatives overseas, using certain apps, or appearing "too religious" can all be interpreted as suspicious. Surveillance therefore takes an active role in shaping Uyghurs as a population the state sees as dangerous.</p>

    <div class="pull-quote">
      <p>Instead of one police officer deciding that someone "looks suspicious," databases and algorithms can label people or entire groups as threats based on everyday behavior, religion, ethnicity, and social connections.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>Connection to Structural Islamophobia</h2>
    <p>Islamophobia in China is structural because it is built into systems of governance. Surveillance technology enables state actors to carry out Islamophobic policy automatically. Technology also allows the state to cover up repression as merely technical or "data-based" — even though it disproportionately targets Uyghur and other Muslim communities. Regular religious and cultural practices become data points.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- DETENTION -->
<div id="page-detention" class="page">
  <div class="page-hero">
    <div class="page-number">Section 06</div>
    <h1>Detention, Prisons, &amp; Human Rights Findings</h1>
    <p>The scale and structure of coercive confinement targeting Uyghur Muslims</p>
  </div>
  <div class="content-area">
    <p>Detention is one of the clearest examples of how Islamophobia in China becomes structural. The state not only stigmatizes Uyghur Muslims but also confines, reeducates, and disciplines them through coercive institutions.</p>

    <div class="image-figure">
      <img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="UHRP chart showing detention and imprisonment status of documented Uyghur cases: 40.9% Prison, 36.1% Unknown, 19.3% Camp, 1.9% Deceased, 1% Released, 0.8% House Arrest">
      <div class="image-caption">Source: Uyghur Human Rights Project (UHRP) — Detention and imprisonment status of documented cases. The majority remain in prison (40.9%) or in camps (19.3%), with 36.1% status unknown.</div>
    </div>

    <h2>The Detention System</h2>
    <p>Reports from Amnesty International, Human Rights Watch, and other researchers describe a large detention system in Xinjiang targeting Uyghurs, as well as Kazakhs and other predominantly Muslim ethnic minorities. Although the Chinese government has described these facilities as "vocational education and training centers" meant to prevent extremism, human rights investigations describe them as part of a broader system of forced political indoctrination, religious repression, surveillance, and punishment.</p>

    <div class="pull-quote">
      <p>The UN Office of the High Commissioner for Human Rights found serious human rights violations in Xinjiang and stated that the scale of discriminatory detention may constitute international crimes, particularly crimes against humanity.</p>
      <cite>OHCHR Assessment, August 2022</cite>
    </div>

    <h2>Conditions Inside</h2>
    <p>Former detainees have described political indoctrination, pressure to renounce religious practices, restrictions on language and prayer, family separation, and fear of abuse. The purpose is not simply to punish crimes after they occur, but to transform people into the image of citizens the state seeks — before they are considered threats. Islamophobia in China structurally treats Uyghur Muslim life as something that must be corrected, monitored, and assimilated under the guise of counterterrorism.</p>

    <div class="info-box">
      <h4>Not Isolated — Systemic</h4>
      <p>The UN finding shows that the issue is not only isolated cases of abuse or poor prison conditions, but a systemic policy framework designed to break down Muslim minority populations. Large numbers of people have been deprived of liberty for reasons tied to religion, ethnicity, family connections, travel history, cultural identity, or alleged extremism.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>Key Facts</h2>
    <div class="law-box">
      <h4>Estimated Scale</h4>
      <p>Over 1.8 million Uyghurs and other Muslims are estimated to have been detained in the camp system at some point since 2017, according to researchers including Adrian Zenz and documents from the Xinjiang Police Files leak.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="law-box">
      <h4>Biometric Collection</h4>
      <p>Authorities collected biometric data — including DNA samples and fingerprints — from subjects in labor camps, creating permanent records tied to surveillance systems.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ECONOMIC -->
<div id="page-economic" class="page">
  <div class="page-hero">
    <div class="page-number">Section 07</div>
    <h1>Economic Restrictions &amp; Forced Labor</h1>
    <p>How economic control extends Islamophobia into labor systems and global supply chains</p>
  </div>
  <div class="content-area">
    <p>In Xinjiang, economic restrictions appear through labor control, restricted movement, coerced employment, and global supply chains. For Uyghur Muslims, economic life is shaped by an extension of the same security system that controls their religion and culture.</p>

    <h2>Labor-Transfer Programs</h2>
    <p>The Chinese state often presents labor-transfer and poverty-alleviation programs as efforts to modernize Xinjiang and provide job training. However, human rights groups and labor researchers argue that these programs involve the coercion of Uyghurs and pressure to leave rural communities for state-assigned work. In this system, economic development becomes another way to discipline Uyghur Muslim life.</p>

    <div class="pull-quote">
      <p>Uyghur communities are treated as economically backward, politically risky, and in need of transformation — yet simultaneously leveraged for forced labor in the production of goods sold in international markets.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>Global Supply Chains</h2>
    <p>The U.S. Department of Labor described the forced labor programs targeting Uyghurs as encompassing prison labor, reeducation-center labor, and labor-transfer programs involving rural "surplus" laborers. These programs have been linked to industries such as textiles, cotton, yarn, tomato products, polysilicon, aluminum, PVC, jujubes, seafood, and other goods exchanged globally.</p>

    <div class="surveillance-grid">
      <div class="surv-cell"><div class="surv-icon">👔</div><h4>Textiles &amp; Cotton</h4><p>Xinjiang produces ~85% of China's cotton, with forced labor documented in picking and processing</p></div>
      <div class="surv-cell"><div class="surv-icon">☀️</div><h4>Solar Polysilicon</h4><p>Much of the world's solar panel supply chain passes through Xinjiang facilities</p></div>
      <div class="surv-cell"><div class="surv-icon">🏭</div><h4>Manufacturing</h4><p>Aluminum, PVC, and electronics linked to reeducation-center production</p></div>
    </div>

    <h2>International Response: UFLPA</h2>
    <div class="info-box">
      <h4>Uyghur Forced Labor Prevention Act (2021)</h4>
      <p>This U.S. law assumes that goods made wholly or partly in Xinjiang are connected to forced labor unless companies can determine otherwise. It directly challenges the economic benefits of repression and pressures corporations to examine whether their supply chains depend on the coercive control of Uyghur Muslims.</p>
    </div>

    <p>The UFLPA represents a key success case: it makes the systemic exploitation of Uyghurs more transparent globally and creates economic incentives for corporations to decouple from forced labor supply chains, directly harming the economic model that sustains Uyghur repression.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- MEDIA -->
<div id="page-media" class="page">
  <div class="page-hero">
    <div class="page-number">Section 08</div>
    <h1>Media, Films, Images, &amp; Propaganda</h1>
    <p>How state media normalizes repression and constructs Uyghur Muslims as the Other</p>
  </div>
  <div class="content-area">
    <p>The powerful Chinese state media helps normalize repression by dividing Uyghurs into "safe" minorities who accept state training and "dangerous" Muslims associated with terrorism. In documentaries presented to the public, the state portrays its policies as necessary responses to violence — giving the audience an emotional narrative in which the state is the protector of order and Uyghur Muslims must be guided and controlled.</p>

    <h2>Edward Said's Orientalism Applied</h2>
    <p>Edward Said's concept of Orientalism helps explain how these representations become politically useful. Said argues that powerful institutions create knowledge about the "Other" in ways that appear neutral but actually serve political purposes. In Xinjiang, state media representations of Uyghur Muslims as backward help make Chinese detention more acceptable and appear more necessary to domestic audiences.</p>

    <div class="pull-quote">
      <p>Uyghur culture is acceptable in mainstream Chinese media when it is patriotic and controlled by the state — but Muslim identity becomes suspicious when it seems resistant to assimilation.</p>
      <cite>David R. Stroup, "Good Minzu and Bad Muslims: Islamophobia in China's State Media" (2021)</cite>
    </div>

    <h2>Representational Strategies</h2>
    <div class="law-box">
      <h4>The "Safe" Minority</h4>
      <p>Uyghurs who participate in state-approved performances are shown as examples of successful ethnic unity. Cultural displays of dance, music, and food are broadcast widely — sanitized of any religious or political content — to present a diversity compatible with Han Chinese nationalism.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="law-box">
      <h4>The "Dangerous" Muslim</h4>
      <p>State documentaries frame Uyghur Muslims who resist assimilation as radicalized threats. CGTN broadcasts portray the camps as educational rescues from terrorism, inverting the reality of coercive detention into a narrative of state benevolence.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="law-box">
      <h4>The International Narrative</h4>
      <p>For foreign audiences, Chinese diplomats and state media argue that criticism of Xinjiang policy constitutes interference in internal affairs and protection of terrorists — weaponizing the language of sovereignty to deflect human rights accountability.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>Why This Matters</h2>
    <p>If audiences repeatedly see Xinjiang described as a place threatened by terrorism and saved by state development, then the general populace may view surveillance and restrictions as reasonable or even humanitarian. This is structural Islamophobia at the level of knowledge production — shaping what counts as truth about Uyghur Muslim life.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- COUNTER-ORGS -->
<div id="page-counter" class="page">
  <div class="page-hero">
    <div class="page-number">Section 09</div>
    <h1>Counter-Organizations, Resistance, &amp; Success Cases</h1>
    <p>The groups challenging Islamophobia in China and the victories won so far</p>
  </div>
  <div class="content-area">
    <p>Although Uyghur Muslims inside China are heavily restricted from organizing, many human rights organizations have created resistance to the current Islamophobic regime through intensive documentation and legal advocacy. Because public protest and independent religious organizing is forbidden in Xinjiang, much of the resistance happens outside China.</p>

    <h2>Key Organizations</h2>

    <div class="org-card">
      <h4>Campaign for Uyghurs</h4>
      <p>An advocacy organization founded by Uyghur diaspora members that campaigns for the rights of Uyghurs in China. The organization works to raise global awareness, support survivors, and pressure governments to take action.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="org-card">
      <h4>World Uyghur Congress</h4>
      <p>The representative body of the Uyghur diaspora, the World Uyghur Congress coordinates international advocacy efforts, represents Uyghur political interests at the UN, and provides a platform for survivors to share testimony.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="org-card">
      <h4>Uyghur Human Rights Project (UHRP)</h4>
      <p>A Washington-based research and advocacy organization that produces detailed documentation on detention, forced labor, surveillance, and other abuses — providing journalists and policymakers with verified evidence.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="org-card">
      <h4>Amnesty International &amp; Human Rights Watch</h4>
      <p>Both organizations have produced extensive, peer-reviewed reports on detention and forced labor in Xinjiang. Their documentation dispels Chinese propaganda portraying camps as altruistic vocational centers, uncovering the true nature of the system.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="section-divider"><span>Success Cases</span></div>

    <h2>Positive Developments</h2>

    <div class="success-item">
      <div class="success-icon">⚖️</div>
      <div>
        <h4>Uyghur Forced Labor Prevention Act (UFLPA)</h4>
        <p>The most significant legislative success: this U.S. law blocks goods made in Xinjiang from entering American markets unless companies can prove they were not produced with forced labor. It directly challenges the economic infrastructure of repression and makes systemic exploitation globally transparent.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="success-item">
      <div class="success-icon">🇺🇳</div>
      <div>
        <h4>UN OHCHR Report (2022)</h4>
        <p>The UN Office of the High Commissioner for Human Rights published an assessment finding that China's treatment of Uyghurs may constitute crimes against humanity. Though China attempted to suppress the report, its publication represents a landmark in international accountability for Islamophobia as state policy.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="success-item">
      <div class="success-icon">📢</div>
      <div>
        <h4>Growing International Coalition</h4>
        <p>Over 40 countries have signed joint statements criticizing China's treatment of Uyghurs at the UN Human Rights Council. The growing coalition — including Muslim-majority countries that China had pressured to remain silent — marks a shift in global willingness to name Islamophobic state violence.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="success-item">
      <div class="success-icon">🏛️</div>
      <div>
        <h4>Genocide Resolutions</h4>
        <p>Multiple national legislatures — including the United States, Canada, the United Kingdom, and the European Parliament — have passed resolutions declaring Chinese treatment of Uyghurs to be genocide or crimes against humanity, increasing diplomatic and reputational costs for Beijing.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

